A '''source text'''<ref name=umdguide>{{cite web|last=User Education Services|title=Primary, Secondary and Tertiary Sources guide|url=http://www.lib.umd.edu/ues/guides/primary-sources|publisher=University of Maryland Libraries|accessdate=12 July 2013|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130703015116/http://www.lib.umd.edu/ues/guides/primary-sources|archivedate=3 July 2013|df=}}</ref><ref>[http://www.library.jcu.edu.au/LibraryGuides/primsrcs.shtml JCU - Primary, Secondary & Tertiary Sources] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050212093611/http://www.library.jcu.edu.au/LibraryGuides/primsrcs.shtml |date=2005-02-12 }}</ref> is a [[writing|text]] (sometimes [[Speech|oral]]) from which [[information]] or ideas are derived. In [[translation]], a source text is the original text that is to be translated into another [[language]].

==Description==
In [[historiography]], distinctions are commonly made between three kinds of source texts:

===Primary===
{{main|Primary source}}
[[Primary source]]s are firsthand written [[evidence]] of history made at the [[time]] of the event by someone who was present. They have been described as those sources closest to the origin of the information or idea under study.<ref name=umdguide /><ref name="ref_">[http://www.library.jcu.edu.au/LibraryGuides/primsrcs.shtml "Library Guides: Primary, secondary and tertiary sources"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050212093611/http://www.library.jcu.edu.au/LibraryGuides/primsrcs.shtml |date=2005-02-12 }}</ref> These types of sources have been said to provide researchers with "direct, unmediated information about the object of study."<!--FOOTNOTE--><ref>{{Citation
|last1=Dalton
|first1=Margaret Steig 
|last2=Charnigo
|first2=Laurie
|title=Historians and Their Information Sources
|url=http://web-archive-sources.org/dalton.pdf
|pages=400–25, at 416 n.3
|journal=[[College & Research Libraries]]
|volume=September
|year=2004
}}, citing U.S. Dept. of Labor, Bureau of Labor Statistics (2003), ''Occupational Outlook Handbook''; {{Citation
